In contrast, GLP-1 immunoreactivity in the CA1 region of 
the hippocampus was preserved in aged mice compared with 
young mice (Fig. 2A and C, young: 23.0 ± 2.8 GLP-1 positive 
cells per 100 nuclei; aged: 26.4 ± 5.6 GLP-1 positive cells per 
100 nuclei, p = 0.597, n = 9 images from 3 mice, respectively). 
In the dentate gyrus (DG) of the hippocampus, GLP-1 
immunoreactivity was also preserved in aged mice compared 
with young mice (Fig. 2B and C, young: 29.0 ± 3.7 GLP-1 
positive cells per 100 nuclei; aged: 32.2 ± 2.7 GLP-1-positive 
cells per 100 nuclei, p = 0.513, n = 9 images from 3 mice, 
respectively). The protein level of proglucagon, a precursor 
protein of GLP-1 in the hippocampus, was consistently 
preserved in aged mice compared with young mice (Fig. 2D 
and E, aged: 106.5 ± 4.1 % that of the young mPFC, p = 0.235, 
n = 4).  
 
